which do turn over.

00:13:15.740 --> 00:13:18.650
So, this is supportive
of Roger's hypothesis.

00:13:21.070 --> 00:13:23.215
Can we image in 15 and 14?

00:13:23.215 --> 00:13:25.520
So, then we went after tricks

00:13:25.520 --> 00:13:30.400
that are done more in
geology or in astrophysics,

00:13:30.400 --> 00:13:32.940
looking at meteorites or whatever.

00:13:33.880 --> 00:13:35.340
Something that was taught to me

00:13:35.340 --> 00:13:38.060
by a colleague, Victoria
Orphan at Cal Tech,

00:13:38.060 --> 00:13:40.660
working on some samples from the ocean

00:13:40.660 --> 00:13:44.060
and this is a machine
that uses a Cesium beam,

00:13:44.060 --> 00:13:47.820
knocks out atoms, secondary ions,

00:13:47.820 --> 00:13:50.180
runs them down something
like a mass spec column

00:13:50.180 --> 00:13:52.580
and then point by point,
you get a collection

00:13:52.580 --> 00:13:57.580
of masses for as many as
seven different atoms.

00:13:58.290 --> 00:14:01.940
And you can make a map, okay?

00:14:01.940 --> 00:14:04.820
So, one of the things that we tried,

00:14:04.820 --> 00:14:09.020
Nick's postdoctoral
advisor, Jack McMahon okay,

00:14:09.020 --> 00:14:12.670
so this goes back a way,
postulated and then proved

00:14:12.670 --> 00:14:15.240
that Agrin, a molecule that secreted

00:14:15.240 --> 00:14:17.180
into the extracellular matrix,

00:14:17.180 --> 00:14:20.510
guides synapse formation for
the neuromuscular synapse.

00:14:20.510 --> 00:14:23.685
So, we said, "well we
have intercostal muscles

00:14:23.685 --> 00:14:27.480
from these mice, what do
the end plates look like?"

00:14:27.480 --> 00:14:29.800
Do we see a signal from this method

00:14:29.800 --> 00:14:32.790
that I just showed you? Yes, okay.

00:14:32.790 --> 00:14:35.820
So, that would be predicted.

00:14:35.820 --> 00:14:37.660
Here it shows you can do this.

00:14:37.660 --> 00:14:41.320
We went from there, to
ask in these samples

00:14:41.320 --> 00:14:43.710
from the mice that Varda grew,

00:14:43.710 --> 00:14:47.230
what about this stuff,
this extracellular matrix,

00:14:47.230 --> 00:14:48.650
is it old?

00:14:48.650 --> 00:14:50.970
And here, you see, doing
the same sort of thing

00:14:50.970 --> 00:14:54.080
on those samples, okay,

00:14:56.150 --> 00:14:59.050
that indeed it is, okay.

00:14:59.050 --> 00:15:00.550
And this, by they way, is myelin.

00:15:00.550 --> 00:15:02.350
Myelin turns out, like you saw,

00:15:02.350 --> 00:15:04.610
maybe if you were paying
attention to the bottom,

00:15:04.610 --> 00:15:07.806
myelin basic protein to
other myelins are old.

00:15:07.806 --> 00:15:10.740
So this is telling you,
if you look at the brain

00:15:10.740 --> 00:15:13.940
and after the majority of
proteins have turned over,

00:15:13.940 --> 00:15:16.220
six months, 18 months later,

00:15:16.220 --> 00:15:18.700
what piece parts are left behind.

00:15:18.700 --> 00:15:23.260
And here, this is the stuff
